> Fragrant and nourishing, our 15-minute Thai Fish Curry is a lovely healthy recipe for busy 
> evenings. Coley is a great tasting white fish with a similar meaty texture to Cod making 
> it a versatile ingredient to use in light and fresh dishes like this one. Its flaky 
> texture works brilliantly with crunchy broccoli, packed with fibre and potassium.

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}(peeled and thinly sliced).

Chop the @broccoli{1}(chopped into florets).

Zest, then halve the @lime{1/2}(zested and halved).

Chop the @coley fillet{2}(chopped into 2cm chunks).

> IMPORTANT: Remember to wash your hands and equipment after handling raw fish.

Heat a splash of @oil{} in a large #saucepan{} over medium-high heat.

Add the onion and broccoli. Stir and cook stirring frequently until the onion has 
softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add the @Thai style spice mix{1}(be careful it's hot! add less if you're not a fan of heat) 
and @ground turmeric{2}.

Stir and cook for ~{1%minute} then pour in the @light coconut milk{200%ml}.

Stir in the @vegetable stock powder{1/2} and the @water{100%ml}. Bring to the boil.

Once boiling, add the coley to the pan and immediately lower the heat.

Pop on a #lid{} (or cover with #foil{}) and simmer until the broccoli is tender and the 
fish cooked through, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The fish is cooked when opaque in the centre.

While the fish is gently poaching, cook the @brown rice & quinoa{1%pack} according to 
pack instructions.

When piping hot, share the rice between your bowls and sprinkle a little lime zest on 
each portion.

When the fish is cooked, remove from the heat and carefully stir in a good squeeze of 
lime juice and the remaining zest.

Season to taste with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}. Spoon on top of your rice. 
Enjoy!